    "answers": [
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/0693f13b4e5fbc345c08faf86414357f?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG&f=y&so-version=2",
                "account_id": 2068768,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1843698,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1843698/kaifei",
                "reputation": 1638,
                "display_name": "Kaifei"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 9,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1359763991,
            "creation_date": 1359763991,
            "body": "<p>nextGaussian() Returns the next pseudorandom, Gaussian (\"normally\") distributed double value with mean 0.0 and standard deviation 1.0 from this random number generator's sequence. (<a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/1.4.2/docs/api/java/util/Random.html#nextGaussian()\">http://docs.oracle.com/javase/1.4.2/docs/api/java/util/Random.html#nextGaussian()<\/a>)<\/p>\n\n<p>So <code>std * rng.nextGaussian();<\/code> should be <code>std * (1 + rng.nextGaussian())/2<\/code>;<\/p>\n\n<p>However, the result may not be the gaussian you want, you need to tune the mean value and std with different <code>a<\/code> and <code>b<\/code> in <code>(a + rng.nextGaussian())/b<\/code><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 14657177,
            "question_id": 14657143
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/ZNjba.png?s=256",
                "account_id": 1185544,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 1159604,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/1159604/foggzie",
                "reputation": 9851,
                "display_name": "Foggzie",
                "accept_rate": 100
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 3,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1359764304,
            "creation_date": 1359763930,
            "body": "<p>I don't think you're interpreting the meaning and purpose of <code>nextGaussian()<\/code> properly.  If you want a number that is in the range <code>[0.0, 1.0)<\/code>, use <code>nextDouble()<\/code> instead.<\/p>\n\n<p><code>nextGaussian()<\/code> uses a mean and a standard deviation, <strong><em>not a simple number range<\/em><\/strong>. Therefore, it has a theoretically infinite range of return values (within the bounds of <code>double<\/code> at least). Read more about <code>nextGaussian()<\/code> in <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/1.4.2/docs/api/java/util/Random.html#nextGaussian%28%29\" rel=\"nofollow\">this java doc<\/a><\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 14657171,
            "question_id": 14657143,
            "last_edit_date": 1359764304
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://i.sstatic.net/4bnfd.jpg?s=256",
                "account_id": 168071,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 2027519,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/2027519/redoacs",
                "reputation": 143,
                "display_name": "redoacs"
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 2,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1359764424,
            "creation_date": 1359764424,
            "body": "<p>I think you are confusing the standard deviation with the range of the values. They are not the same thing. <\/p>\n\n<p>Taken from the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Standard_deviation#Interpretation_and_application\" rel=\"nofollow\">Standard Deviation Wikipedia<\/a> entry: <\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>For example, each of the three populations {0, 0, 14, 14}, {0, 6, 8, 14} and {6, 6, 8, 8} has a mean of 7. Their standard deviations are 7, 5, and 1, respectively.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n",
            "answer_id": 14657236,
            "question_id": 14657143
        },
        {
            "owner": {
                "profile_image": "https://www.gravatar.com/avatar/2c52d8862ec3b13e1c9cb14d37ca2257?s=256&d=identicon&r=PG",
                "account_id": 99829,
                "user_type": "registered",
                "user_id": 269454,
                "link": "https://stackoverflow.com/users/269454/lujop",
                "reputation": 13964,
                "display_name": "lujop",
                "accept_rate": 51
            },
            "content_license": "CC BY-SA 3.0",
            "score": 1,
            "is_accepted": false,
            "last_activity_date": 1359764470,
            "creation_date": 1359764470,
            "body": "<p>To my understand Javadoc for <code>nextGaussian()<\/code> says:<\/p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Returns the next pseudorandom, Gaussian (\"normally\") distributed double value with mean 0.0 and standard deviation 1.0 from this random number generator's sequence.<\/p>\n<\/blockquote>\n\n<p>It doesn't says the value will be from -1 to 1. Then if you want it to be in that values you can discard outside values or take -1 or 1 when the values are outside.<\/p>\n",
            "answer_id": 14657240,
            "question_id": 14657143
        }
    ],
